  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Which are the best poems about India?",
  "response": "India has been a rich source of inspiration for poets across centuries, reflecting its diverse culture, history, spirituality, and socio-political landscape. Here is a list of some of the best poems about India by both Indian and international poets:\n\n### **Classical and Pre-Independence Era**\n1. **\"Where the Mind is Without Fear\" by Rabindranath Tagore** (from *Gitanjali*)  \n   A timeless prayer for a free, enlightened, and united India.\n\n2. **\"The Lotus\" by Toru Dutt**  \n   A beautiful allegory comparing India to the sacred lotus, blending Hindu symbolism with poetic elegance.\n\n3. **\"On the Banks of the Ganges\" by Harindranath Chattopadhyay**  \n   A lyrical ode to the spiritual and cultural essence of India.\n\n4. **\"The Indian Weavers\" by Sarojini Naidu**  \n   A poignant poem that captures the struggles and artistry of Indian weavers.\n\n### **Post-Independence and Modern Era**\n5. **\"Freedom\" by Agha Shahid Ali**  \n   A reflective poem on India\u2019s independence and its complex aftermath.\n\n6. **\"The Quilt\" by Ismat Chughtai**  \n   Though primarily a short story, it contains poetic reflections on Indian society.\n\n7. **\"The Unknown Citizen\" by Nissim Ezekiel**  \n   A satirical take on urban life in post-independence India.\n\n8. **\"The Stone Age\" by Kamala Das**  \n   A powerful exploration of identity, gender, and cultural heritage in India.\n\n### **Spiritual and Philosophical Themes**\n9. **\"The Song of Kabir\" by Kabir**  \n   A mystic poem that delves into the essence of spirituality and unity.\n\n10. **\"Tulsidas\u2019s Ramcharitmanas (excerpts)**  \n    A poetic retelling of the Ramayana in Awadhi, blending devotion and literary brilliance.\n\n### **International Poets on India**\n11. **\"The Golden Threshold\" by Sarojini Naidu**  \n    Though written by an Indian, it inspired international poets like W.B. Yeats to write about India.\n\n12. **\"Gunga Din\" by Rudyard Kipling**  \n    A controversial but famous poem about India during the British colonial era.\n\n13. **\"India\" by Allen Ginsberg**  \n    A Beat poet\u2019s exploration of India\u2019s spiritual and cultural landscape.\n\n### **Contemporary Voices**\n14. **\"The Algebra of Loving India\" by Arundhathi Subramaniam**  \n    A modern meditation on the complexities of loving India.\n\n15. **\"Partition\" by Tishani Doshi**  \n    A haunting reflection on the trauma of India\u2019s partition.\n\n16. **\"The Untitled Indian\" by Jeet Thayil**  \n    A contemporary poet\u2019s take on India\u2019s chaotic, vibrant, and paradoxical nature.\n\n### **Regional and Vernacular Poetry**\n17. **\"Vachanas\" by Basavanna** (Kannada)  \n    Mystical and social reformist poetry from medieval Karnataka.\n\n18. **\"Subramania Bharati\u2019s Poems\" (Tamil)**  \n    Revolutionary and patriotic verses from Tamil Nadu.\n\n19. **\"Ghalib\u2019s Ghazals\" (Urdu)**  \n    Mirza Ghalib\u2019s profound explorations of love, loss, and existentialism.\n\nThese poems offer a glimpse into the soul of India, celebrating its beauty, critiquing its flaws, and exploring its multifaceted identity. Each poem is a testament to the enduring power of poetry in capturing the essence of a nation.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
